<div class="intro">
<div class="welcome">
Welcome to ECS, the School  of Electronics and Computer Science at the University of Southampton. ECS is one of the world's leading centres for 
<a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041106085107/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/research/">research</a>, 
<a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041106085107/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/about/teaching/">teaching</a>, <a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041106085107/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/business/">enterprise and innovation</a> in Electronics, Electrical Engineering and Computer Science.
<div class="sig">Head of School: <a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041106085107/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/people/wh">Professor Wendy Hall</a></div>
</div>
<div class="headline"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041106085107/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/636"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041106085107im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_636_img&amp;maxw=200&amp;maxh=150&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=bb53ff9d43dccb3e6a11beacadd0e8cb" alt="Morpho Rhetenor butterfly" border="0" width="200" height="123" class="thumbnail" /></a><h2>Headline News</h2><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041106085107/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/636">Butterflies’ wings dazzle with science</a></h3><p>The brilliant dazzle of butterflies’ wings could hold the key to a new type of optical material, called photonic crystals. According to Dr Luca Plattner, who undertook research in the School's Microelectronics Research Group, our understanding of the way that light is reflected from the wings of butterflies could lead to the fabrication of new photonic crystals.</p><p></p></div></div><div class='rightside'>

